06326nam a22009615i 9789812309518DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010si     fo  d z      eng d  a2010353181  a97898123095187 a10.1355/97898123095182doi  a(DE-B1597)492089  a(OCoLC)1041991214  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aBP63.I5bV37 2010 4aBP63.I5 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a297.622200aVarieties of Religious Authority :bChanges and Challenges in 20th Century Indonesian Islam /ced. by Azyumardi Azra, Kees van Dijk, Nico J. G. Kaptein. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (229 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tABOUT THE CONTRIBUTORS -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. The Redefinition of Religious Authority among South Asian Muslims from 1919 to 1956 -- t2. Understanding Al-Imam’s Critique of Tariqa Sufism -- t3. Traditional Islam and Modernity: Some Notes on the Changing Role of the Ulama in Early Twentieth Indonesia -- t4. The Role and Identity of Religious Authorities in the Nation State: Egypt, Indonesia, and South Africa Compared -- t5. Authority Contested: Mathla’ul Anwar in the Last Years of the New Order -- t6. Struggle for Authority: Between Formal Religious Institution and Informal-local Leaders -- t7. The Indonesian Madrasah: Islamic Reform and Modernization of Indonesian Islam in the Twentieth Century -- t8. From Apolitical Quietism to Jihadist Activism: “Salafis”, Political Mobilization, and Drama of Jihad in Indonesia -- t9. From handling Water in a Glass to Coping with an Ocean: Shifts in Religious Authority in Indonesia -- t10. Religious Authority and the Supernatural -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe twentieth century was a fascinating period of profound political, social and economic changes in Indonesia. These changes contributed to the diversification of the religious landscape and as a result, religious authority was redistributed over an increasing number of actors. Although many Muslims in Indonesia continued to regard the ulama, the traditional religious scholars, as the principle source of religious guidance, religious authority has become more diffused and differentiated over time. The present book consists of contributions which all deal with the multi-facetted and multidimensional topic of religious authority and aim to complement each other. Most papers deal with Indonesia, but two dealing with other countries have been included in order to add a comparative dimension. Amongst the topics dealt with are the different and changing roles of the ulama, the rise and role of Muslim organizations, developments within Islamic education, like the madrasa, and the spread of Salafi ideas in contemporary Indonesia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthorityxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aAuthority--Religious aspects--Islam. 0aIslamic renewalzIndonesia. 0aIslamic renewal--Indonesia. 0aReligious awakeningxIslam. 0aReligious awakening--Islam. 0aUlamazIndonesia. 0aUlama--Indonesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh1 aAzra, Azyumardi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurhanudin, Jajat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijk, Kees van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeillard, Andrée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaborieau, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan, Noorhaidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaptein, Nico J. G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a